# Git-ignored paths symlinked from the main tree into every new worktree.
#
# WHY this file exists. `git worktree add` materializes only TRACKED files, so a fresh
# worktree starts without any of these — and the failure is silent: the session simply
# works without the file and never learns it existed. Worse, anything CREATED at one of
# these paths inside a worktree dies with it. `git worktree remove` refuses a dirty or
# untracked worktree, which reads as "git will stop me", but ignored paths are excluded
# from that check entirely and are deleted with no warning at all. A file was lost that
# way in a sibling repo. A symlink is what prevents it: removing the worktree then
# removes only the link, never the content.
#
# One path per line. `#` comments and blank lines are ignored. A path that does not
# exist in the main tree is skipped, so listing an optional one costs nothing.

# Planning and research documents — the largest body of un-versioned work here, and the
# one a worktree most needs. Not versioned by design (`.gitignore`), which is exactly
# why it has to be linked rather than left to `git worktree add`.
artifacts

